{"parse":{"title":"Glue semantics","pageid":12474917,"revid":826299824,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Glue semantics</b>, or simply <b>Glue</b> (Dalrymple et al. 1993; Dalrymple 1999, 2001), is a linguistic theory of semantic composition and the syntax-semantics interface which assumes that meaning composition is constrained by a set of instructions stated within a formal logic (<a href=\"/wiki/Linear_logic\" title=\"Linear logic\">linear logic</a>).  These instructions, called <i>meaning constructors</i>, state how the meanings of the parts of a sentence can be combined to provide the meaning of the sentence.\n</p><p>Glue was developed as a theory of the syntax-semantics interface within the linguistic theory of <a href=\"/wiki/Lexical_functional_grammar\" title=\"Lexical functional grammar\">lexical functional grammar</a>, and most work within Glue has been conducted within that framework.  LFG-Glue assumes that the syntactic structure that is most relevant for meaning assembly is the functional structure, a structure which represents abstract syntactic predicate argument structure and relations like subject and object.  In this setting, a meaning constructor for an <a href=\"/wiki/Intransitive_verb\" title=\"Intransitive verb\">intransitive verb</a> states that the verb combines with the meaning of its subject to produce a meaning for the sentence.  This is similar in some respects to the view of the syntax-semantics interface assumed within <a href=\"/wiki/Categorial_grammar\" title=\"Categorial grammar\">categorial grammar</a>, except that abstract syntactic relations like <i>subject</i> and <i>object</i> rather than relations such as <i>to-the-left-of</i> are involved in meaningful constructor specifications.  Glue analyses within other syntactic formalisms have also been proposed; besides LFG, glue analyses have been proposed within <a href=\"/wiki/HPSG\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"HPSG\">HPSG</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Context-free_grammar\" title=\"Context-free grammar\">context-free grammar</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Categorial_grammar\" title=\"Categorial grammar\">categorial grammar</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Tree-adjoining_grammar\" title=\"Tree-adjoining grammar\">tree-adjoining grammar</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Glue is a theory of the syntax-semantics interface which is compatible not only with various syntactic frameworks, but also with different theories of semantics and meaning representation.  Semantic formalisms that have been used as the meaning languages in glue semantics analyses include versions of <a href=\"/wiki/Discourse_representation_theory\" title=\"Discourse representation theory\">discourse representation theory</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Intensional_logic\" title=\"Intensional logic\">intensional logic</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/First-order_logic\" title=\"First-order logic\">first-order logic</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Natural_semantic_metalanguage\" title=\"Natural semantic metalanguage\">natural semantic metalanguage</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Glue_semantics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Lexical_functional_grammar\" title=\"Lexical functional grammar\">Lexical functional grammar</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Glue_semantics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Dalrymple, Mary, John Lamping, and Vijay Saraswat (1993). <i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20060720190358/http://acl.ldc.upenn.edu/E/E93/E93-1013.pdf\">LFG semantics via constraints</a></i>.  In Proceedings of the Sixth Meeting of the European ACL (pp.&#160;97\u2013105). University of Utrecht.</li>\n<li>Dalrymple, Mary (Ed.). (1999). Semantics and syntax in Lexical Functional Grammar: The resource logic approach. Cambridge, MA: MIT Press.  <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-262-04171-5\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-262-04171-5\">0-262-04171-5</a></li>\n<li>Dalrymple, Mary (2001). Lexical Functional Grammar, No. 42 in Syntax and Semantics Series. New York: Academic Press.  <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-12-613534-7\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-12-613534-7\">0-12-613534-7</a></li></ul>\n<dl><dt>Specific</dt></dl>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation conference\">Asudeh, Ash; Crouch, Richard (2001). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://web.stanford.edu/group/cslipublications/cslipublications/HPSG/2/Ash-Crouch-pn.pdf\">\"Glue Semantics for HPSG\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>.  In van Eynde, Frank; Hellan, Lars; Beermann, Dorothee. <i>Proceedings of the 8th International HPSG Conference</i>. CSLI Publications. pp.&#160;1\u201319.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=conference&amp;rft.atitle=Glue+Semantics+for+HPSG&amp;rft.btitle=Proceedings+of+the+8th+International+HPSG+Conference&amp;rft.pages=1-19&amp;rft.pub=CSLI+Publications&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.aulast=Asudeh&amp;rft.aufirst=Ash&amp;rft.au=Crouch%2C+Richard&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fweb.stanford.edu%2Fgroup%2Fcslipublications%2Fcslipublications%2FHPSG%2F2%2FAsh-Crouch-pn.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGlue+semantics\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation conference\">Frank, Anette; van Genabith, Josef (2001). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://web.stanford.edu/group/cslipublications/cslipublications/LFG/6/pdfs/lfg01frankgenabith.pdf\">\"Glue Tag: Linear Logic based Semantics Construction for LTAG \u2013 and What it Teaches Us About the Relation Between LFG and LTAG\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>.  In Butt, Miriam; King, Tracy Holloway. <i>Proceedings of the LFG01 Conference</i>. pp.&#160;104\u2013126.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=conference&amp;rft.atitle=Glue+Tag%3A+Linear+Logic+based+Semantics+Construction+for+LTAG+%E2%80%93+and+What+it+Teaches+Us+About+the+Relation+Between+LFG+and+LTAG&amp;rft.btitle=Proceedings+of+the+LFG01+Conference&amp;rft.pages=104-126&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.aulast=Frank&amp;rft.aufirst=Anette&amp;rft.au=van+Genabith%2C+Josef&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fweb.stanford.edu%2Fgroup%2Fcslipublications%2Fcslipublications%2FLFG%2F6%2Fpdfs%2Flfg01frankgenabith.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGlue+semantics\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Glue_semantics&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"m